# Data Source Configuration

File: `data.tf`

```hcl id="gbbqys"
# Find the latest Ubuntu 22.04 AMI published by Canonical
data "aws_ami" "own_ami_ubuntu_IND" {
  most_recent = true
  owners      = ["099720109477"] # Canonical's AWS account ID

  filter {
    name   = "name"
    values = ["ubuntu/images/hvm-ssd/ubuntu-jammy-22.04-amd64-server-*"]
  }

  filter {
    name   = "virtualization-type"
    values = ["hvm"]
  }
}
```

## Explanation

Instead of hardcoding an AMI ID, this activity dynamically fetches the latest Ubuntu 22.04 AMI from AWS.

This approach is preferred because:

* AMI IDs change across regions
* newer AMIs are released regularly
* hardcoded AMIs may become outdated

The `most_recent = true` parameter ensures Terraform always selects the latest matching AMI.

The owner ID:

* `099720109477`

belongs to Canonical, which is the official publisher of Ubuntu AMIs on AWS.

The filters ensure:

* Ubuntu 22.04
* SSD-backed storage
* AMD64 architecture
* HVM virtualization type

